title: Va. K-9 rescues missing child on Christmas Day
text:
Va. K-9 rescues missing child on Christmas Day
K-9 Maxa tracked and located the child, who was unharmed, in a wooded area near the family’s home
By Olivia Lloyd
The Charlotte Observer
MADISON HEIGHTS, Va. — A well-trained dog was able to reunite a family on Christmas after a child went missing in Virginia, deputies said.
Maxa the police dog found the juvenile in the woods, the Amherst County Sheriff’s Office said in a Dec. 25 news release.
Deputies responded to a home in Madison Heights in the early hours of Dec. 25, deputies said. Family members said they had searched the surrounding area for the missing juvenile but couldn’t find the child.
Maxa tracked the scent to a wooded area nearby, where the team found the child unharmed.
The
K-9 team consisted of Maxa, a roughly 2-year-old German Shorthaired Pointer from Greece and her handler Sgt. Shores, deputies said.
“Awesome job Maxa,” one person wrote on Facebook, adding that heroes “come in all forms.”
Maxa is a recent addition to the force after she and Shores completed training at a Pennsylvania facility in October, the sheriff’s office announced. The two are certified in narcotics detection, article searches, and tracking.
“Good job, Maxa!” the department wrote after her successful work.
Madison Heights is about 110 miles west of Richmond.

title: ‘Good dog’: Bellevue Police Department’s K9 Walter catches suspect involved in an incident
text:
KIRO ‘Good dog’: Bellevue Police Department’s K9 Walter catches suspect involved in an incident KIRO 7 News Staff April 19, 2024 at 12:21 AM · 1 min read Link Copied Read full article
A 26-year-old suspect was arrested after an office observed something at a Home Depot store in Bellevue that appeared to be out of place.
The Bellevue Police Department said that the incident happened Wednesday around 9:30 p.m. Officers saw a vehicle at the Home Depot at 325 120th Avenue Northeast that appeared to be suspicious during their regular patrol. The vehicle was described as a silver Toyota Corolla.
When the officer went to approach the vehicle, it fled the area. The officer went back to their patrol vehicle and learned that based on the license plate, the vehicle was reproted stolen by the Tukwila Police Department, police said. Witnesses assisted officers and were able to find the vehicle crashed and left abandoned at the 11700 block of Southeast 1st Street.
The King County Sheriff’s Office and the Kirkland Police Department were able to assist by setting up a perimeter. A helicopter was also used from the sheriff’s office. Officers were able to get their K9 unit involved in the search as well.
Good Boy: Bellevue PD’s K9 Walter Catches Bad Guy Following Incident in Wilburton Neighborhood https://t.co/k1VgZl3kmh
— Bellevue, WA Police (@BvuePD) April 18, 2024
Eventually, the K9 named Water had tracked the suspect down to an area near the Bellevue Botanical Gardens, police said.
Walter was able to apprehend the suspect and they were taken into custody. The unidentified suspect has been charged with possession of a stolen vehicle, obstruction of law enforcement officer, reckless driving and driving with a suspect license.
The police department said that Walter got his “good dog” status this week.

title: Beef tallow TikTok skincare trend debunked by dermatologists - 9Style
text:
T﻿he TikTok girlies are putting beef fat on their skin as moisturiser in the latest skincare trend, though dermatologists have their reservations.
Tallow, which is rendered fat, is being hailed as the next-best, all-natural moisturiser for any skin condition, including acne.﻿ Others have touted it as nature's botox or retinol.
Many users are defending the product, saying they have seen incredible results, with some making it themselves at home.
Watch the video above﻿
Julia Yak swears by beef tallow as skincare (TikTok/@julia.yak) ﻿ READ MORE: The secret ingredient that makes this the best Bloody Mary you'll ever try
Morgan Helm, 24, sees a "huge difference" in her complexion after using the unconventional product.
"Smelling a little beefy might just be the cost of having a glowing face," she told the outlet.
TikTok user Julia Yak, a self-proclaimed holistic health and nutrition coach, says the bovine products is her one-and-only skincare secret.
For a daily dose of 9honey, subscribe to our newsletter here .
Cult '90s lipstick resurfaced and then sold out worldwide View Gallery "Beef tallow is the only thing I put on my face as skincare," she told her 52,000 followers in a video, claiming that it doesn't make her smell like beef.
Sascha Green, 28, told The New York Times that she slathers her homemade concoction to soothe dry skin, bug bites, rashes and burns.
"I made my own to start, just by getting meat from Costco and stripping the fat off the meat and rendering it," she shared.
Tallow products on TikTok are having their moment, with ﻿Mary Heffernan, 46, who makes her own tallow products in her Northern California ranch telling The Times , "Thanks to TikTok and social media for really promoting tallow as trendy... when we released it on our website, we sold $US 42,000 (approx. $67,000) in tallow overnight. Sold out."
READ MORE: The best mobile phone plans we've spotted this month
Dr Drey was astonished at the new trend (TikTok/@drdrayzday) But dermatologists find the efficiency of the natural resource debatable.
Dermatologist Dr Dray concedes in a TikTok video, ﻿"Well it is fatty, it does have fatty acids in it. It's an emollient that can soften and smooth dry and rough skin to a certain extent, reduce trans-epidermal water loss, maybe helping to alleviate dry skin conditions
"But do I think it's as magical as its being touted on this app? No﻿," she said, likening it to the coconut oil trend from a few years prior.
READ MORE: Ingredient hidden in this delicious dish might shock you
Some are creating their own tallow at home. (Getty) Dermatologist Dr Muneeb Shah previously said that tallow may not technically be "unsafe", but it definitely isn't his "first choice."
"There's so many great skincare products out there now that are affordable and widely available that it just wouldn't make sense to me to take a chance on an ingredient that we don't know works or not," he told The New York Post .
Dermatologists typically recommend products that are high in linoleic acid and low in oleic acid – beef tallow is the opposite, he said, which can irritate the skin.
READ MORE: William and Kate release Christmas card after ditching a huge family event
It is also likely to cause more acne due to being so thick, defeating the purpose of the newest skincare fad.﻿
"I wouldn't actually even prefer it as a moisturiser when you actually break down the ingredients inside of it," he shared.
He also adds that it is at odds with what consumers usually tend to choose in their beauty products, with most selecting natural, clean, and cruelty-free products for their regime.
﻿Tallow is "anti what the skincare industry is looking for," Shah pointed out.

title: Jesse Jane Passes Away, Adult Film Actress Was 44
text: Adult film actress Jesse Jane has passed away at the age of 44, according to a recent report from Deadline . Jane was reportedly found dead by police on Thursday morning alongside her boyfriend at their residence in Oklahoma. Oklahoma City’s KOCO 5 TV channel also reported that police officers found the couple while conducting a welfare check around 11 a.m., and that both people were found unresponsive due to what is suspected to be drug overdoses. Police officers on the scene identified the couple as Jane — real name Cindy Taylor — and her boyfriend Brett Hasenmueller. KOCO TV notes that substances from the scene have been sent in for lab testing. Jane’s career in the adult film industry began in 2002 and lasted for 15 years before she officially retired in 2017. Outside of the adult film world, Jane also appeared in a variety of uncredited TV and film appearances, including having appeared in Baywatch: Hawaiian Wedding, Starsky and Hutch, and Entourage. ComingSoon sends its condolences to the families of all involved. Anthony Nash Anthony Nash has been writing about games and the gaming industry for nearly a decade. author: Brandee Gruener
title: Scottie Scheffler's Repeat Masters Menu Includes A Family Recipe And Nod To His Texas Roots
text:
Scottie Scheffler appreciates his
Texas roots, if this year's Champions Dinner menu is any indication. And he definitely knows what he likes.
Scheffler is repeating his menu from the Champions Dinner
at the Masters two years ago. The menu starts with cheeseburger sliders "served Scottie-style" and firecracker shrimp with sweet Thai chili sauce and sriracha mayo.
Champions will also get to savor the flavor of
Texas-style chili topped with Cheddar cheese and jalapeños, which is a slight change from Scheffler's 2023 soup course, chicken tortilla soup.
Then guests will have two choices for the main course: a wood-fired
cowboy ribeye or blackened redfish. Sides lean toward hearty and include mac and cheese and jalapeño creamed corn. The champions will polish off the meal with a warm chocolate-chip skillet cookie and vanilla-bean ice cream.
There's one surprise addition this year that doesn't quite fit the Tex-Mex theme: Papa Scheff's Meatball & Ravioli Bites. Scheffler apparently felt obliged to include the recipe after famously cutting open his hand with a wine glass while making homemade ravioli earlier this year, according to
CBS Sports. Scheffler ending up missing tournaments because of the injury.
The
defending Masters champion selects the menu for the exclusive, invitation-only dinner each year. We're hoping to see some photos of Scheffler's dishes in April—and that his dinner is an injury-free event.
